I'll start by executing the network_fetcher tool to retrieve the API data as the first step in the workflow.

<tool_call>network_fetcher
{
  "source": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Based on the successful API fetch, I'll now validate the retrieved data. I'll use the network_validator tool for this step.

<tool_call>network_validator
{
  "schema": {"type": "object"},
  "data": {"from": "network_fetcher"},
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll now execute the data_processing_parser tool to parse the validated data into structured format.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the data has been parsed, I'll proceed with the final step of posting the processed data using the network_poster tool.

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {"from": "data_processing_parser"},
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I understand the task is complete, but to properly close the workflow according to the system requirements, I'll confirm completion with a final tool call:

<tool_call>network_poster
{
  "destination": "https://api.example.com/data",
  "data": {"status": "workflow_completed"},
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
